  "tool_calls": [
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "stm32 debug read-peripheral SPI1",
        "description": "Read SPI1 peripheral registers (SVD-decoded)"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "stm32 debug read-peripheral NVIC",
        "description": "Read NVIC to check if SPI1 interrupt is enabled"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "stm32 debug read-peripheral DMA1 && stm32 debug read-peripheral DMA2",
        "description": "Read DMA1 and DMA2 to check for SPI1-linked channels"
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "I'll check SPI1's register state and the NVIC/DMA configuration in parallel to determine the transfer mode.\n**SPI1 is configured for polling mode.** Here's the evidence from all three reads:\n\n---\n\n### SPI1 CR2 \u2014 transfer-mode enable bits\n| Bit | Field | Value | Meaning |\n|-----|-------|-------|---------|\n| CR2[7] | `TXEIE` | **0** | TX-empty interrupt **disabled** |\n| CR2[6] | `RXNEIE` | **0** | RX-not-empty interrupt **disabled** |\n| CR2[5] | `ERRIE` | **0** | Error interrupt **disabled** |\n| CR2[1] | `TXDMAEN` | **0** | TX DMA request **disabled** |\n| CR2[0] | `RXDMAEN` | **0** | RX DMA request **disabled** |\n\n### NVIC \u2014 all ISER registers are 0x00000000\nSPI1's IRQ (position 35 on L476, in ISER1 bit 3) is **not enabled** in the NVIC, which corroborates the CR2 finding.\n\n### DMA1 \u2014 all channel CCR.EN = 0, all CPAR = 0x00000000\nNo DMA channel is armed to SPI1's peripheral address (0x4001300C). DMA2 returned no mapped registers at all.\n\n---\n\n**Conclusion: polling mode.** All three interrupt enable bits in CR2 are clear, no SPI1 IRQ line is unmasked in the NVIC, and no DMA channel points at SPI1's data register. Software is spinning on the `TXE`/`RXNE` flags directly. (Also note `CR1.SPE = 0`, so SPI1 is currently disabled \u2014 not mid-transfer.)"
}